SIMPLE: spurn
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Spurn
<hw>Spurn</hw> <pr>(sp⟦ucir⟧rn)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Spurned</conjf>
<pr>(sp⟦ucir⟧rnd)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Spurning</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>spurnen</ets> to kick
against, to stumble over, AS. <ets>spurnan</ets> to kick, offend; akin
to <ets>spura</ets> spur, OS. & OHG. <ets>spurnan</ets> to kick, Icel.
<ets>spyrna</ets>, L. <ets>spernere</ets> to despise, Skr.
<ets>sphur</ets> to jerk, to push. ⟦root⟧171. See <er>Spur</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To drive back or away, as with the foot; to
kick.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[The bird] with his foot will <qex>spurn</qex> adown his cup.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I <qex>spurn</qex> thee like a cur out of my way.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To reject with disdain; to scorn to receive or
accept; to treat with contempt.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What safe and nicely I might well delay⟦br⟧
By rule of knighthood, I disdain and <qex>spurn</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Domestics will pay a more cheerful service when they find
themselves not <qex>spurned</qex> because fortune has laid them at their
master's feet.</q> <rj><qau>Locke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spurn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Spurn
<hw>Spurn</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To kick or toss up the
heels.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The miller <qex>spurned</qex> at a stone.</q>
<rj><qau>Chaucer.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The drunken chairman in the kennel <qex>spurns</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Gay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To manifest disdain in rejecting anything; to make
contemptuous opposition or resistance.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Nay, more, to <qex>spurn</qex> at your most royal image.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spurn</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Spurn
<hw>Spurn</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A kick; a blow with the
foot.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What defense can properly be used in such a despicable encounter
as this but either the slap or the <qex>spurn</qex>?</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Disdainful rejection; contemptuous
treatment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The insolence of office, and the <qex>spurns</qex>⟦br⟧
That patient merit of the unworthy takes.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mining)</fld> <def>A body of coal left to sustain
an overhanging mass.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Spurner</ent>⟦br⟧
